    <segment id="1" parent="2" relname="background">
With our discussion on usability concepts, it may be a good time to focus a bit more on 
users.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="15" relname="span"> I believe the starting point is asking ourselves, &quot;who are our users?&quot;</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="2" relname="elaboration"> This requires 
us to discover the background of our users, including their user experience levels, their 
goals and needs, and other things that might tie into design.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="12" relname="span"> The cultural aspect is indeed 
important,</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="3" relname="circumstance"> particularly when we are designing specifically for an international audience.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="14" relname="span"> 

Marcus raises a few interesting questions in his article in Interactions: </segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="5" relname="list"> When Is A User 
Not A User?</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="5" relname="list"> Who Are We?</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="5" relname="list"> What Do We Do?</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="14" relname="background">  (Marcus in his numerous articles that are 
featured in Interactions, provides the basis for a good debate on many HCI issues.)</segment>
